{"title_page": "Allen T. Caperton", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Allen T. Caperton\n|image        = Allen T. Caperton - Brady-Handy.jpg\n|jr/sr        = United States Senator\n|state        = [[West Virginia]]\n|term_start   = March 4, 1875\n|term_end     = July 26, 1876\n|predecessor  = [[Arthur I. Boreman|Arthur Boreman]]\n|successor    = [[Samuel Price]]\n|office1      = [[Congress of the Confederate States|Confederate States Senator]]<br>from [[Virginia]]\n|term_start1  = January 22, 1864\n|term_end1    = May 10, 1865\n|predecessor1 = [[William Ballard Preston|William B. Preston]]\n|successor1   = Constituency abolished\n|office2      = Member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] from [[Monroe County, West Virginia|Monroe County]]\n|term_start2  = December 7, 1857\n|term_end2    = December 2, 1861\n|predecessor2 = [[Alexander Clarke (Virginia politician)|Alexander Clarke]]\n|successor2   = [[Wilson Lively]]\n|term_start3  = December 6, 1841\n|term_end3    = December 5, 1842\n|predecessor3 = [[Augustus A. Chapman]]\n|successor3   = [[William Adair (Virginia politician)|William Adair]]\n|birthname    = Allen Taylor Caperton\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1810|11|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Union, West Virginia|Union]], [[Virginia]], [[United States|U.S.]]<br>(now [[West Virginia]])\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1876|7|26|1810|11|21}}\n|death_place  = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Virginia]]<br>[[Yale College|Yale University]]\n}}\n'''Allen Taylor Caperton''' (November 21, 1810 \u2013 July 26, 1876) was an American politician who was a [[United States Senator]] from the State of [[West Virginia]] in 1875&ndash;1876. He was a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. He had served in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] and [[Virginia State Senate]] before the [[American Civil War]]. During the Civil War, he served as a [[Confederate States Senate|Confederate States Senator]].\n\n==Early life==\nCaperton, son of [[Hugh Caperton]] and Jane Erskine, was born near [[Union, Monroe County, West Virginia|Union]], [[Monroe County, West Virginia]] (now [[West Virginia]]) on November 21, 1810. At the age of 14, he traveled by horseback to [[Huntsville, Alabama]], to attend school. He later graduated from the [[University of Virginia]] at [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]], then graduated from [[Yale College]] in 1832. He studied law in [[Staunton, Virginia]], was admitted to the bar and practiced law. He was married to Harriett Echols.\n\n==Political career==\nCaperton served as a member of the Virginia House of Delegates in 1841\u20131842. He was elected a member of the Virginia Senate in 1844, and served until 1848. He was a member of the Virginia House of Delegates again from 1857 to 1861. In 1850 he was a delegate to the [[Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1850|State constitutional convention]]. In 1861, he was a member of the [[Virginia Secession Convention of 1861|Virginia Secession Convention]].\n\nDuring the Civil War, he was elected by the legislature of Virginia to be a member of the [[Confederate States Senate]] in which he served until 1865.\n\nAfter the war, he was the first ex-Confederate elected to the United States Senate, entering office as a Democrat from West Virginia and served from March 4, 1875, until his death in Washington, D.C., July 26, 1876. He was interred in Green Hill Cemetery, Union, West Virginia.\n\nHis residence near [[Union, Monroe County, West Virginia|Union, West Virginia]], \"[[Elmwood (Union, West Virginia)|Elmwood]],\" was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1976.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a|dateform=Mdy}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1790\u20131899)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{CongBio|C000130}} Retrieved on March 23, 2009\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Allen T. Caperton}}\n* {{fg|7619539}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|cs-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Ballard Preston|William Preston]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of members of the Confederate Senate|Confederate States Senator (Class 2) from Virginia]]|years=1864\u20131865|alongside=[[Robert M. T. Hunter|Robert Hunter]]}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box\n| before=[[Arthur I. Boreman|Arthur Boreman]]\n| state=West Virginia\n| class=1\n| years=March 4, 1875 \u2013 July 26, 1876 \n| alongside=[[Henry G. Davis|Henry Davis]]\n| after=[[Samuel Price]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{C.S. Senators}}\n{{USSenWV}}\n{{Portal bar|American Civil War|Biography|Politics|Virginia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caperton, Allen T.}}\n[[Category:1810 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Senators]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:People from Union, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People of Virginia in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of West Virginia in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:United States senators from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia lawyers]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:Virginia Secession Delegates of 1861]]\n[[Category:Caperton family of Virginia and West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Yale College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:West Virginia lawyers]]\n\n\n{{Virginia-politician-stub}}\n{{WestVirginia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Allen T. Caperton\n|image        = Allen T. Caperton - Brady-Handy.jpg\n|jr/sr        = United States Senator\n|state        = [[West Virginia]]\n|term_start   = March 4, 1875\n|term_end     = July 26, 1876\n|predecessor  = [[Arthur I. Boreman|Arthur Boreman]]\n|successor    = [[Samuel Price]]\n|office1      = [[Congress of the Confederate States|Confederate States Senator]]<br>from [[Virginia]]\n|term_start1  = January 22, 1864\n|term_end1    = May 10, 1865\n|predecessor1 = [[William Ballard Preston|William B. Preston]]\n|successor1   = Constituency abolished\n|office2      = Member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] from [[Monroe County, West Virginia|Monroe County]]\n|term_start2  = December 7, 1857\n|term_end2    = December 2, 1861\n|predecessor2 = [[Alexander Clarke (Virginia politician)|Alexander Clarke]]\n|successor2   = [[Wilson Lively]]\n|term_start3  = December 6, 1841\n|term_end3    = December 5, 1842\n|predecessor3 = [[Augustus A. Chapman]]\n|successor3   = [[William Adair (Virginia politician)|William Adair]]\n|birthname    = Allen Taylor Caperton\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1810|11|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Union, West Virginia|Union]], [[Virginia]], [[United States|U.S.]]<br>(now [[West Virginia]])\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1876|7|26|1810|11|21}}\n|death_place  = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Virginia]]<br>[[Yale College|Yale University]]\n}}\n'''Allen Taylor Caperton''' (November 21, 1810 \u2013 July 26, 1876) was an American politician who was a [[United States Senator]] from the State of [[West Virginia]] in 1875&ndash;1876. He was a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. He had served in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] and [[Virginia State Senate]] before the [[American Civil War]]. During the Civil War, he served as a [[Confederate States Senate|Confederate States Senator]].\n\n==Early life==\nCaperton, son of [[Hugh Caperton]] and Jane Erskine, was born near [[Union, Monroe County, West Virginia|Union]], [[Monroe County, West Virginia]] (now [[West Virginia]]) on November 21, 1810. At the age of 14, he traveled by horseback to [[Huntsville, Alabama]], to attend school. He later graduated from the [[University of Virginia]] at [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]], then graduated from [[Yale College]] in 1832. He studied law in [[Staunton, Virginia]], was admitted to the bar and practiced law. He was married to Harriett Echols.\n\n==Political career==\nCaperton served as a member of the Virginia House of Delegates in 1841-1842. He was elected a member of the Virginia Senate in 1844, and served until 1848. He was a member of the Virginia House of Delegates again from 1857 to 1861. In 1850 he was a delegate to the [[Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1850|State constitutional convention]]. In 1861, he was a member of the [[Virginia Secession Convention of 1861|Virginia Secession Convention]].\n\nDuring the Civil War, he was elected by the legislature of Virginia to be a member of the [[Confederate States Senate]] in which he served until 1865.\n\nAfter the war, he was the first ex-Confederate elected to the United States Senate, entering office as a Democrat from West Virginia and served from March 4, 1875, until his death in Washington, D.C., July 26, 1876. He was interred in Green Hill Cemetery, Union, West Virginia.\n\nHis residence near [[Union, Monroe County, West Virginia|Union, West Virginia]], \"[[Elmwood (Union, West Virginia)|Elmwood]],\" was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1976.<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a|dateform=Mdy}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1790\u20131899)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{CongBio|C000130}} Retrieved on March 23, 2009\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Allen T. Caperton}}\n* {{fg|7619539}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|cs-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Ballard Preston|William Preston]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of members of the Confederate Senate|Confederate States Senator (Class 2) from Virginia]]|years=1864\u20131865|alongside=[[Robert M. T. Hunter|Robert Hunter]]}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box\n| before=[[Arthur I. Boreman|Arthur Boreman]]\n| state=West Virginia\n| class=1\n| years=March 4, 1875 \u2013 July 26, 1876 \n| alongside=[[Henry G. Davis|Henry Davis]]\n| after=[[Samuel Price]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{C.S. Senators}}\n{{USSenWV}}\n{{Portal bar|American Civil War|Biography|Politics|Virginia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caperton, Allen T.}}\n[[Category:1810 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Senators]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:People from Union, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People of Virginia in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of West Virginia in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:United States senators from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Virginia lawyers]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:Virginia Secession Delegates of 1861]]\n[[Category:Caperton family of Virginia and West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Yale College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:West Virginia lawyers]]\n\n\n{{Virginia-politician-stub}}\n{{WestVirginia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1841-1842 \u2192 1841\u20131842", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_T._Caperton"}
{"title_page": "Rachel Weston", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Representative\n| image       =\n| imagesize   =\n| name        = Rachel Weston\n| caption     = \n| state       = Vermont\n| state_house = Vermont\n| district    = [[Chittenden-3-3 Vermont Representative District, 2002-2012|Chittenden-3-3]] \n| term_start  = 2007\n| term_end = 2012\n| predecessor = John Patrick Tracy\n| party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 1981\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| alma_mater  = [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]<br>[[University of Vermont]]\n| occupation  = \n| residence   = [[Burlington, Vermont]]\n| spouse      = \n| partner     = \n| religion    = \n| website     = [http://rachelweston.org/ rachelweston.org]\n}}\n'''Rachel M. Weston''' (born 1981) is a former Vermont State Representative for the [[Chittenden-3-3 Vermont Representative District, 2002-2012|Chittenden-3-3 District]] representing Old North End, Downtown, and Waterfront in Burlington, Vermont. First elected in 2006, Weston stepped down from the legislature in 2012 to take a job working on women's political participation in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bromage|first=Andy|title=Burlington Rep. Rachel Weston to Step Down|url=http://7d.blogs.com/blurt/2012/01/burlington-rep-rachel-weston-to-step-down.html|work=7d.blogs.com|accessdate=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nShe graduated from the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] in 2003 (BA, Anthropology) and the [[University of Vermont]] in 2006 (MPA,  Public Administration). Prior to pursuing a Masters, she was a public school teacher and worked with community non-profit organizations. She served as President of the UVM Graduate Student Senate, and as a [[Campus Compact]] Civic Engagement Fellow.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rachelweston.org/about_us.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724122751/http://rachelweston.org/about_us.html |archivedate=2010-07-24 }}</ref><ref>http://www.uvm.edu/about_uvm/?Page=stories/students/weston.html</ref> She was elected to serve in the 2007\u20132008, 2009\u20132010, and 2011-2012 legislatures.  Weston was the youngest serving member of the [[Vermont State Legislature]]. She served as a member of the House Ways and Means Committee and the Natural Resources and Energy Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yeonetwork.org/content/vermont-state-representative-rachel-weston |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226040725/http://www.yeonetwork.org/content/vermont-state-representative-rachel-weston |archivedate=2009-12-26 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rachelweston.org/ Campaign site]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weston, Rachel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the Vermont House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Women state legislators in Vermont]]\n[[Category:University of Massachusetts Amherst alumni]]\n\n\n{{Vermont-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox State Representative\n| image       =\n| imagesize   =\n| name        = Rachel Weston\n| caption     = \n| state       = Vermont\n| state_house = Vermont\n| district    = [[Chittenden-3-3 Vermont Representative District, 2002-2012|Chittenden-3-3]] \n| term_start  = 2007\n| term_end = 2012\n| predecessor = John Patrick Tracy\n| party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 1981\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| alma_mater  = [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]<br>[[University of Vermont]]\n| occupation  = \n| residence   = [[Burlington, Vermont]]\n| spouse      = \n| partner     = \n| religion    = \n| website     = [http://rachelweston.org/ rachelweston.org]\n}}\n'''Rachel M. Weston''' (born 1981) is a former Vermont State Representative for the [[Chittenden-3-3 Vermont Representative District, 2002-2012|Chittenden-3-3 District]] representing Old North End, Downtown, and Waterfront in Burlington, Vermont. First elected in 2006, Weston stepped down from the legislature in 2012 to take a job working on women's political participation in the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bromage|first=Andy|title=Burlington Rep. Rachel Weston to Step Down|url=http://7d.blogs.com/blurt/2012/01/burlington-rep-rachel-weston-to-step-down.html|work=7d.blogs.com|accessdate=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nShe graduated from the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] in 2003 (BA, Anthropology) and the [[University of Vermont]] in 2006 (MPA,  Public Administration). Prior to pursuing a Masters, she was a public school teacher and worked with community non-profit organizations. She served as President of the UVM Graduate Student Senate, and as a [[Campus Compact]] Civic Engagement Fellow.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rachelweston.org/about_us.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724122751/http://rachelweston.org/about_us.html |archivedate=2010-07-24 }}</ref><ref>http://www.uvm.edu/about_uvm/?Page=stories/students/weston.html</ref> She was elected to serve in the 2007-2008, 2009-2010, and 2011-2012 legislatures.  Weston was the youngest serving member of the [[Vermont State Legislature]]. She served as a member of the House Ways and Means Committee and the Natural Resources and Energy Committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yeonetwork.org/content/vermont-state-representative-rachel-weston |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226040725/http://www.yeonetwork.org/content/vermont-state-representative-rachel-weston |archivedate=2009-12-26 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n=