mpion in 1946 and 1947. She won the silver medal in 1950\n\n== Records==\n=== Personal records ===\n{{PersonalRecordsTop}}\n{{PersonalRecordsSport|Women's [[speed skating]]}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|500 m|1:02.50|10.03.1951|Warszawa\u00a0(POL)|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1000 m|2:07.00|11.03.1951|Warszawa\u00a0(POL)|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|1500 m|3:23.80|10.03.1951|Warszawa\u00a0(POL)|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|3000 m|7:08.40|11.02.1950|Moskau\u00a0(RUS)|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsMiddle|5000 m|12:27.10|22.01.1950|Zakopane\u00a0(POL)|}}\n{{PersonalRecordsBottom}}\n<ref name=speedskatingnews />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Sports links}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sedzimir-Krawcow, Krystyna}}\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Polish female speed skaters]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n\n\n{{Poland-speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SportsOlympic", "label": "safe", "comment": ".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krystyna_S%C4%99dzimir-Krawc%C3%B3w"}
{"title_page": "Charles Plympton Smith", "text_new": "{{other people||Charles Smith (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Charles Plympton Smith''' (born June 1, 1954, [[Burlington, Vermont]]) is a banker and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician from the U.S. state of [[Vermont]] who served in the [[Vermont House of Representatives]].  The son of banker and state senator [[Frederick Plympton Smith]], he received a B.A. from [[Harvard College]] in 1978, following which he attended the [[University of Melbourne]], Melbourne Australia on a one-year [[Rotary Foundation Scholarship]]. From 1975-1978 he served two terms in the Vermont House of Representatives, alternating semesters between Harvard and the legislature, which meets only in the spring. He was nominated by both the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and Republican parties.\n\nIn 1980, he was appointed to the [[Vermont Public Service Board]]. From 1981-1983 he was Staff Director and Administrative Assistant for then-Congressman [[James Jeffords]]. From 1984-1987 he was Vice-President of Sales and Marketing for Transphase Systems, Inc. in California. From 1988-1996 he was District Vice-President of [[KeyBank]], National Association in Burlington, Vermont, then President and Senior Commercial lender until 2002.\n\nIn January 2003, he was appointed Secretary to the [[Vermont Agency of Human Services]] by Governor [[Jim Douglas]]. From February 2005 until March 2006 he was Secretary of the Vermont Agency of Administration. On January 27, 2006, he was named president of the [[Snelling Center for Government]] and served in this role until November 2009. He is now a management consultant residing in Burlington and has taken on interim roles such as President of Vermont PBS (2014-2015), President of the Vermont Symphony Orchestra (2015-2016), and COO of Vermont Energy Investment Corporation (2016-2017). He is also a Principal in the building and management of the largest solar-power array in Vermont at Whitcomb Farm in Essex, Vermont.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mynbc5.com/article/essex-farm-now-home-to-vermont-s-largest-solar-array/3323902|title=Essex farm now home to Vermont's largest solar array|first=Stewart|last=Ledbetter|date=5 June 2015|publisher=|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nSmith's board memberships include or have included Cathedral Square Corporation; New England Culinary Institute; Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Vermont (current Chairman); Vermont Energy Investment Corporation; United Way of Chittenden County, as Chair of its Community Investment Committee; Dental Dental of Vermont; Greater Burlington Industrial Corporation; and the Board of Trustees of [[Champlain College]].\n\nHe lives in Burlington, Vermont with his wife, Amy Mellencamp, and their two children, Emily Mellencamp Smith and Charles Plympton Smith V. Charles is the younger brother of former U.S. Congressman [[Peter Plympton Smith]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060207193826/http://www.adm.state.vt.us/smith_bio.htm State of Vermont biography]\n*[http://www.snellingcenter.org/ Snelling Center announcement]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060911171543/http://www.champlain.edu/news/archives2/news_display.php?article=01-03-02a.php Champlain College announcement]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Charles Plympton}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of Vermont]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Vermont Republicans]]\n[[Category:Members of the Vermont House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Vermont-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Charles Smith (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Charles Plympton Smith''' (born June 1, 1954, [[Burlington, Vermont]]) is a banker and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician from the U.S. state of [[Vermont]] who served in the [[Vermont House of Representatives]].  The son of banker and state senator [[Frederick Plympton Smith]], he received a B.A. from [[Harvard College]] in 1978, following which he attended the [[University of Melbourne]], Melbourne Australia on a one-year [[Rotary Foundation Scholarship]]. From 1975-1978 he served two terms in the Vermont House of Representatives, alternating semesters between Harvard and the legislature, which meets only in the spring. He was nominated by both the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and Republican parties.\n\nIn 1980, he was appointed to the [[Vermont Public Service Board]]. From 1981-1983 he was Staff Director and Administrative Assistant for then-Congressman [[James Jeffords]]. From 1984-1987 he was Vice-President of Sales and Marketing for Transphase Systems, Inc. in California. From 1988-1996 he was District Vice-President of [[KeyBank]], National Association in Burlington, Vermont, then President and Senior Commercial lender until 2002.\n\nIn January 2003, he was appointed Secretary to the [[Vermont Agency of Human Services]] by Governor [[Jim Douglas]]. From February 2005 until March 2006 he was Secretary of the Vermont Agency of Administration. On January 27, 2006, he was named president of the [[Snelling Center for Government]] and served in this role until November 2009. He is now a management consultant residing in Burlington and has taken on interim roles such as President of Vermont PBS (2014-2015), President of the Vermont Symphony Orchestra (2015-2016), and COO of Vermont Energy Investment Corporation (2016-2017). He is also a Principal in the building and management of the largest solar-power array in Vermont at Whitcomb Farm in Essex, Vermont.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mynbc5.com/article/essex-farm-now-home-to-vermont-s-largest-solar-array/3323902|title=Essex farm now home to Vermont's largest solar array|first=Stewart|last=Ledbetter|date=5 June 2015|publisher=|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nSmith\u2019s board memberships include or have included Cathedral Square Corporation; New England Culinary Institute; Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Vermont (current Chairman); Vermont Energy Investment Corporation; United Way of Chittenden County, as Chair of its Community Investment Committee; Dental Dental of Vermont; Greater Burlington Industrial Corporation; and the Board of Trustees of [[Champlain College]].\n\nHe lives in Burlington, Vermont with his wife, Amy Mellencamp, and their two children, Emily Mellencamp Smith and Charles Plympton Smith V. Charles is the younger brother of former U.S. Congressman [[Peter Plympton Smith]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060207193826/http://www.adm.state.vt.us/smith_bio.htm State of Vermont biography]\n*[http://www.snellingcenter.org/ Snelling Center announcement]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060911171543/http://www.champlain.edu/news/archives2/news_display.php?article=01-03-02a.php Champlain College announcement]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Charles Plympton}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of Vermont]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Vermont Republicans]]\n[[Category:Members of the Vermont House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Vermont-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Plympton_Smith"}
{"title_page": "Noor Jehan (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Cleanup film|date=March 2019}}{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{short description|1967 film by Mohammed Sadiq}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Noor Jehan\n| image          = Noor Jehan poster.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = Mohammed Sadiq\n| producer       = [[Sheikh Mukhtar]]\n| starring       = [[Meena Kumari]]<br />[[Pradeep Kumar]]\n| music          = [[Roshan (music director)|Roshan]]\n| cinematography = V. Avdhut\n| editing        = Waman Rao\n| distributor    = \n| studio         = \n| released       = {{Film date|1967|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 140 mins\n| language       = Hindustani\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Noor Jehan''''' is a [[1967 in film|1967]] [[Bollywood]] [[film]] produced by [[Sheikh Mukhtar]] and directed by Mohammed Sadiq.\n\n[[Roshan (music director)|Roshan]] was the [[music director]]. Hit songs from the movie include \"Aap Jabse Qareeb Aaye Hain\" sung by [[Mohammed Rafi]] and [[Asha Bhosle]] and \"Sharaabi Sharaabi\" sung by [[Suman Kalyanpur]].\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Meena Kumari]] as  [[Nur Jahan|Noor Jehan]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/unwind/the-tale-of-a-majestic-leader/articleshow/61968302.cms | title=The tale of a majestic leader | date=8 December 2017 | newspaper=Pune Mirror | first=Vinutha | last=Mallya | accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Pradeep Kumar]] as [[Jahangir|Prince Salim]]\n* [[Rehman (actor)|Rehman]] as Emperor [[Akbar]]\n* [[Lalita Pawar]]\n* [[Nigar Sultana (actress)|Nigar Sultana]]\n* [[Johnny Walker (actor)|Johnny Walker]]\n* [[Mukri]]\n* [[Helen (actress)|Helen]]\n* [[Veena (actress)|Veena]]\n* [[Tun Tun]]\n* [[Murad (actor)|Murad]]\n* [[Sheikh Mukhtar]]\n* [[Sohrab Modi]]\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1968 - Won [[15th Filmfare Awards|Filmfare award]] for Best Art Direction - '''''A. A. Majid'''''\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Noor Jehan\n| type         = soundtrack\n| artist       = [[Roshan (music director)|Roshan]]\n| cover        = \n| released     = \n| recorded     = Unknown\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Soundtrack|Film soundtrack]]\n| length       = \n| label        = <div style=\"white-space: nowrap;\">\n| producer     = [[Sheikh Mukhtar]]\n| prev_title   = ''[[Bahu Begum]]'' \n| prev_year    = 1967\n| year         = 1967\n| next_title   = ''[[Anokhi Raat]]''\n| next_year    = 1968\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_lyrics = [[Shakeel Badayuni]]\n| all_music = [[Roshan (music director)|Roshan]]<ref name=\"Noor Jehan soundtrack\">{{cite web | title=Noor Jehan (1968) | website=Hindigeetamala | url=http://www.hindigeetmala.net/movie/noor_jehan.htm | accessdate=2019-03-14}}</ref>\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 31:30\n| title1 = Raat Ki Mehfil Sooni Sooni\n| extra1 = [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n| length1 = 3:06\n| title2 = Sharaabi Sharaabi\n| extra2 = [[Suman Kalyanpur]]\n| length2 = 4:11\n| title3 = Aayi Waade Bahaarein Le Ke\n| extra3 = Suman Kalyanpur\n| length3 = 4:46\n| title4 = Aap Jabse Qareeb Aaye Hain\n| extra4 = [[Mohammed Rafi]], [[Asha Bhosle]]\n| length4 = 3:39\n| title5 = Kisi Se Na Kehna\n| extra5 = Asha Bhosle\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = Wo Mohabbat Wo Wafaein\n| extra6 = Mohammed Rafi\n| length6 = 3:27\n| title7 = Mohabbat Ho Gayi\n| extra7 = Asha Bhosle\n| length7 = 3:12\n| title8 = Aa Gaya Lab Pe Afsana\n| extra8 = Asha Bhosle, [[Usha Mangeshkar]]\n| length8 = 5:40\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|tt0139502}}\n[[Category:1967 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1960s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Urdu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian historical films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Jahangir]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Akbar]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Cleanup film|date=March 2019}}{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{short description|1967 film by Mohammed Sadiq}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Noor Jehan\n| image          = Noor Jehan poster.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = Mohammed Sadiq\n| producer       = [[Sheikh Mukhtar]]\n| starring       = [[Meena Kumari]]<br />[[Pradeep Kumar]]\n| music          = [[Roshan (music director)|Roshan]]\n| cinematography = V. Avdhut\n| editing        = Waman Rao\n| distributor    = \n| studio         = \n| released       = {{Film date|1967|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 140 mins\n| language       = Hindustani\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Noor Jehan''''' is a [[1967 in film|1967]] [[Bollywood]] [[film]] produced by [[Sheikh Mukhtar]] and directed by Mohammed Sadiq.\n\n[[Roshan (music director)|Roshan]] was the [[music director]]. Hit songs from the movie include \"Aap Jabse Qareeb Aaye Hain\" sung by [[Mohammed Rafi]] and [[Asha Bhosle]] and \"Sharaabi Sharaabi\" sung by [[Suman Kalyanpur]].\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Meena Kumari]] as  [[[[Nur Jahan|Noor Jehan]]<ref>{{cite news | url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/unwind/the-tale-of-a-majestic-leader/articleshow/61968302.cms | title=The tale of a majestic leader | date=8 December 2017 | newspaper=Pune Mirror | first=Vinutha | last=Mallya | accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Pradeep Kumar]] as [[[[Jahangir|Prince Salim]]\n* [[Rehman (actor)|Rehman]] as Emperor [[Akbar]]\n* [[Lalita Pawar]]\n* [[Nigar Sultana (actress)|Nigar Sultana]]\n* [[Johnny Walker (actor)|Johnny Walker]]\n* [[Mukri]]\n* [[Helen (actress)|Helen]]\n* [[Veena (actress)|Veena]]\n* [[Tun Tun]]\n* [[Murad (actor)|Murad]]\n* [[Sheikh Mukhtar]]\n* [[Sohrab Modi]]\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1968 - Won [[15th Filmfare Awards|Filmfare award]] for Best Art Direction - '''''A. A. Majid'''''\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name  